  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chblue"><font class="h1font"> Intermediate Decks</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td colspan="2"><font class="h1font">Nashiq&#39;s Burning Desert</font></td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Rating</Font></TD><TD><table width='55' border='0' cellspacing='0' cellpadding='0'><tr><td background='/magination/gfx/5star.gif'><img src='/lotr/gfx/trans.gif' width='1' height='25'></td></tr></table><font size=1>(2.75)</font> | <A HREF="/magination/decks/decks.php?reviews=27133">Read Reviews</A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Author</font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> <A HREF="http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=10347">Daniel "Dartax" Burke</A></FONT> <font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=10347&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a></font></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Description</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> This deck uses Nahara and Nashiq to play with the discard pile using spells, powers, and effects to discard energy from opposing creatures.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Submitted</Font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> February 4, 2003</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Cards</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Magi:<br />
Nahara<br />
(Starting: Szhar, Forgotten Tales)<br />
<br />
Nashiq<br />
(Starting: Darbok, Warrior Olum, Dessicate)<br />
<br />
Drajan<br />
(Starting: Sand Hyren, Uban)<br />
<br />
Creatures:<br />
Darbok x3<br />
Izmer x3<br />
Sand Hyren x3<br />
Szhar x3<br />
Uban x3<br />
Warrior Olum x3<br />
Wind Hyren x2<br />
<br />
Spells:<br />
Crushing Sands x2<br />
Dessicate x3<br />
Forgotten Tales x3<br />
Oasis x2<br />
Sandswirl x2<br />
Sunburn x2<br />
<br />
Relics:<br />
Amulet of Sand x2<br />
Bottled City x2<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(507)">Relic Stalker</a> x2<br />
<br />
Total: 40 cards<br />
   </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> In many ways, Ryan Reymont helped test this deck, even though his variation is a bit different. In case you are wondering, he managed to pull a Crystal Vision and is using that instead of Bottled City along with 3 Sandstorm Orshaa instead of the Sand Hyren. He&#8217;s also been tinkering with some other alterations. Overall, our two decks share a similar theme. <br />
<br />
Nahara serves two purposes as the first magi. The first is his starting cards. Second, his power works well with this deck. You may or may not use the Forgotten Tales on your first turn. Either way, both your first and second magi in this deck make great use of cards in the discard pile, so you&#8217;ll want to have a few there. As a nice bonus, Nahara starts with a creature that can help you draw some more cards. By drawing cards and filling in your discard pile, you&#8217;ll not only set up your next magi, you&#8217;ll be able to use this magi&#8217;s power frequently. Izmer, Warrior Olum and Uban all have powers that do not reference themselves. Copy these, or useful creature powers in an opponent&#8217;s discard pile, to make good use of your first magi. <br />
<br />
Nashiq is the central magi of this deck. It was after a real good second look at this magi that I chose to build a deck centered around her power. Ryan is the one who quickly identified Nahara as a great first magi to use with her. Although her energize is small, this magi could be treated as energizing for as much as seven energy each turn. All you need to do is make sure the card you wish to save energy with has a copy in the discard pile. Use her power to shuffle a copy from the discard pile back into the deck and then play the copy in your hand for three less to a minimum of one. For example, with Sand Hyren in play under your control, you can play a Warrior Olum for a cost of one energy by combining her power with the savings the hyren would grant because the Warrior Olum is one of her starting cards. Even without the Sand Hyren, you could use Dessicate for a cost of two (plus one off of one of your creatures) as long as you used her power on a Dessicate in the discard pile. <br />
<br />
Drajan was chosen mostly because a lot of players here use a lot of effects in attacks. It doesn&#8217;t hurt that he increases the cost of opposing powers, too. Since he pulls the Sand Hyren (used in my version listed here) and Uban, he also has some definite potential with the deck itself. This is your last ditch effort magi. Although, other than the Forgotten Tales, you won&#8217;t be able to play with the discard pile like you could with the first two magi. <br />
<br />
As for the deck&#8217;s general strategy, use spells, powers, and effects to discard energy from opposing creatures, then attack the magi. It works a lot like a Cald deck in many ways, except you can bounce Sunburn around as well. <br />
<br />
Here&#8217;s a few tricks you can use under standard conditions. <br />
<br />
Use Uban to discard a card from your hand and do damage at the same time. Follow up with the Darbok to place Uban back in your hand to even more devastating damage. If the discarded card was a creature with a useful power while still on Nahara, use his power to shuffle it back into your deck should you choose to do so. Discard a copy of a card you keep in your hand while using Nashiq to setup the conditions for her power to save you energy. <br />
<br />
Izmer has a free power to discard one energy. It works great with Sunburn. He&#8217;s also in here to allow you to use an effect to discard energy when you play a d&#8217;Resh relic. This should help against burrowed creatures. Just as the Amulet of Sand also introduces an effect that can cut through Olabra and burrow. Although, it may be easier to Sandswirl the offending magi or creature for a turn or more. <br />
<br />
Want to &#8220;shutoff&#8221; the effect or power of an opposing magi or creature for several turns? You can do it cheap with Nashiq as long as you have one copy of Sandswirl in the hand, and another in the discard pile. By shuffling the one back into your deck, you can now Sandswirl the offending card for four turns (which includes your current turn and your next if it&#8217;s not multi-player), for as little as one energy. Subsequent turns will increase the cost after that. <br />
<br />
In game testing so far, being frozen or having the powers cost one more does not stop this deck. <br />
<br />
However, being frozen and having to deal with the penalties of Laranel, the Ice Queen, does shutdown this deck. <br />
<br />
The first possibility with the Ice Queen is to Sandswirl the offending magi for as many turns as possible. While the Sandswirl counts down, you&#8217;ll have that time to resume play as normal. This could be an expensive option. Then again, with Ice Queen, nothing is going to be cheap or easy except possibly playing creatures and attacking outright. With an energize of eight to deal with on top of the Ice Queen&#8217;s effect, this won&#8217;t be easy. <br />
<br />
Another possibility might be to have an Izmer in play, play a Sunburn on an opposing creature. Follow this up with playing a d&#8217;Resh relic, and you can target the creature using Izmer&#8217;s effect instead of its power without having to pay for being frozen or the Ice Queen&#8217;s effect. If you can keep firing off effects that discard energy, such as another d&#8217;Resh relic or the effect from the Amulet of Sand, you may make up the extra initial cost on that Sunburn. At least she doesn&#8217;t give her frozen creatures invulnerability like another Nar magi, so Sunburn can still work nicely with your attacks. <br />
<br />
Both spells mentioned here actually only target a creature or magi once. So, the Ice Queen&#39;s effect would only apply that one time. <br />
<br />
Here are some possible alternates for some of the rares. <br />
Drajan &#8212; Ythra <br />
Sand Hyren &#8212; Habob or Drahkar <br />
Wind Hyren &#8212; Olum Digger <br />
Bottled City &#8212; Sun Glasses or Tomorrow&#39;s Jewel <br />
<br />
<br />
An after thought.... <br />
Why did I post this? No one believed that this deck could rock. Not being a "premium" member at the time, I couldn&#39;t reply to the reviews. Oh, well. Maybe, someday, others will find out the beauty and effectiveness of this side of d&#39;Resh. Until then, keep trying your illusions. Those decks are annoying at times, but I don&#39;t think I&#39;ve lost to one yet.... and that&#39;s even with decks that couldn&#39;t hit magi directly, hehehe. Oh, yeah. The locals that have faced this deck in action fear it, that includes me. Not many of my decks can deal with this (it has been refined and tuned a bit since I posted this). </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/magination/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/magination/decks/decks.php?reviews=27133"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=27133" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/magination/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></td></tr></table></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
